{
  "title": "Raspberry Pi Storage",
  "story": [
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "b69c1b6621f79996",
      "text": "The default storage for all models of Raspberry Pi is a micro SD card. While you can buy micro SD cards that can hold TBs of data, they do not perform as fast as the magnetic or sold state disk storage in most laptop computers. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "24611aa39baea2a3",
      "text": "Fortunately, since 2020 the Raspberry Pi bootloader can boot from external storage connected to the USB 3.1 port. You can connect SATA and NVMe drives and boot from them but they are constrained by the speed of the USB bus. Perhaps a future iteration of the Raspberry Pi will support a higher speed storage connection. For more information about Pi 4 bootloader for USB storage see [https://jamesachambers.com/new-raspberry-pi-4-bootloader-usb-network-boot-guide/ James Chambers' guide].\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "1738b047fca9306c",
      "text": "I currently use a Raspberry Pi 4 with 4 GB of RAM as a remote desktop computer and it boots from a Kingston 240 GB A400 SATA 3 2.5\" SSD (model SA400X37/240G) in a Inateck 2.5 Hard Drive enclosure, USB 3.0 UASP Supported FE2002. The [https://pibenchmarks.com/ Pibenchmarks] score for this drive is 6023, which is not the fastest by any means but faster than SD or a USB thumb drive.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "e43dcea35c23d7d2",
      "text": "I also have a 500 GB Crucial P2 NVMe M.2 SSD and a MOKiN SSD Enclosure that is a little bit faster with a Pibenchmark of 7575. I am not sure that benchmark is as fast as it should be, I recently learned about controversy around this SSD drive and others for which allegedly the manufacturer swapped in lower performing chips after industry benchmarking. I might try cloning the Kingston drive to the Crucial drive to use it as the boot disk in the future. "
    }
